s of exposure to photographic technology, both the required jargon and background knowledge to comfortably engage with an often-technical field. In our present era of film studies, this is no longer the case. The interviews collected here are informative not only on matters of technique, but also on the ways in which practitioners formulate their methodologies, work with directors, and engage with the many logistical hurdles of visual storytelling. The result is an oral history of the past forty years of filmmaking and the cinematography it has produced.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCinematographersvInterviews. 0aCinematography. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / Direction & Production.2bisacsh1 aColeman, Lindsay, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchaefer, Roberto, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2022z978311149185140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848643740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438486437423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438486437/original  a978-3-11-149185-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles